ABUJA – As the All Progressives Con­gress (APC) concluded its screening of the 23 presi­dential aspirants on Tues­day, it has emerged that President Muhammadu Buhari, APC gover­nors and the leadership of the party may have resolved to field a North­ern candidate in the 2023 presidential election. A source at a meeting of the par­ty’s governors on Tuesday at the in Asokoro, Abuja, said the emergence of former Vice President Atiku Abubakar as the standard bearer of the opKebbi State Governor’s Lodge position Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) has thrown span­ners in the works for earlier consideration of a Southern candidate. ­ The source told Daily In­dependent that the governors did not just agree to field a Northern candidate, they equally narrowed their search to possible first choice of Sani Ahmed Yerima, former gover­nor of Zamfara State with Sen­ate President, Ahmad Lawan, coming a distant second in the pecking order. -Advertisement- According to him, the reasoning of the governors was that Atiku Abubakar is such a formidable political opponent that it may require only characters like Buhari to halt his ascent to power in 2023. He said that the governors recalled that Buhari narrowly defeated Atiku in 2019, noting that with the Buhari era fad­ing away, it will be difficult for a Southern candidate to square with Atiku without the party receiving bruises. The APC governors, Dai­ly Independent also learnt, did a thorough review of the strengths and weaknesses of the all four presidential aspi­rants from the North, and nar­rowed their choice to Senator Yerima. The meeting which also had in attendance governors from South-East and South-West, was said to have placed premi­um on retaining their hold on power rather than pacifying any of the political zones with the presidential slot. Meanwhile, the final day of the presidential screening exer­cise witnessed the appearance of Vice President Yemi Osin­bajo, Godswill Akpabio, Abu­bakar Badaru, Ahmad Lawan, Ben Ayade, Kayode Fayemi, Yahaya Bello, Ike Obasi Moke­lu, Ogbonn